<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1059,1308,1419]" pageId="5" pageNumber="964">
D i a g n o s i s: The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirsch" authorityYear="1871" box="[468,594,1309,1330]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="966" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[468,594,1309,1330]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="964">Aphelocerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
KIRSCH was revised in 2005 (OPITZ 2005). This work included a key to species. 
<taxonomicName box="[578,774,1338,1359]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="964" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nolus">
<emphasis box="[578,774,1338,1359]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="964">Aphelocerus nolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens key out to 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="964">A. hespenheidei</emphasis>
OPITZ, from which they differ by showing broader and less acuminate phallobasic lobes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1059,1434,1573]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1058,211,321]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="965" pageId="5" pageNumber="964">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 5.0 mm; width 
<quantity box="[673,753,1434,1456]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="5" pageNumber="964" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,1434,1456]" captionStart="Figs 266-269" captionStartId="94.[151,191,1506,1528]" captionTargetBox="[152,1060,216,1486]" captionTargetId="figure@94.[152,1060,196,1490]" captionTargetPageId="94" captionText="Figs 266-269: Habitus; (266) Aphelocerus nolus; (267) A. sparicapillus; (268) A. tigra; (269) A. yaguare." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746794" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746794/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="964">Fig. 266</figureCitation>
. Color: Black; few white setae at frontal sides, row of white setae on metepisternum. Head: Genae and epicranium extended; gena wrinkled behind eyes; interocular depression and frontal umbo shallow; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[513,583,1522,1544]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="964">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) capitate, funicular antennomeres filiform, progressively shorter and wider towards capitulum, capitulum not compact; eyes finely facetted, eye narrower than frons (EW/FW 20/40). Thorax: Pronotum proper (
<figureCitation box="[962,1051,211,233]" captionStart="Figs 101-117" captionStartId="75.[151,191,1477,1499]" captionTargetBox="[152,1030,198,1448]" captionTargetId="figure@75.[152,1030,198,1465]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="Figs 101-117: Pronota; (101) Aphelocerus ligulus; (102) A. yoro; (103) Ridica achira; (104) R. merida; (105) Ampleris cacuminis; (106) Plocamocera catalexis; (107) Aphelocerus tigra; (108) A. sparicapillus; (109) A. nolus; (110) A. magnipannus; (111) Pyticeroides desodes; (112) Cregya petalosa; (113) C. livida; (114) C. tobagoensis; (115) C. maura; (116) Pujoliclerus flavidus; (117) Amboakis collucoatis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746756" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746756/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="965">Fig. 109</figureCitation>
) subglobose, very finely punctate (PW/PL 78/92); elytra short and boldly convex, disc with striae of very small setiferous punctures (EL/EW 215/60). Abdomen: Pygidium transverse 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[254,261,299,321]" pageId="6" pageNumber="965">/</emphasis>
scutiform; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[530,618,299,321]" captionStart="Figs 201-206" captionStartId="83.[151,191,1264,1286]" captionTargetBox="[153,1059,191,1248]" captionTargetId="figure@83.[153,1059,191,1248]" captionTargetPageId="83" captionText="Figs 201-206: Aedeagi; (201) Aphelocerus copanus; (202) A. ligulus; (203) A. magnipannus; (204) A. nodus; (205) A. nolus; (206) A. sparicapillus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746772" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746772/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="965">Fig. 205</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1058,337,388]" pageId="6" pageNumber="965">Variation: Frons width is sex dimorphic with male frons proportionally wider. Also, male antennae are proportionally longer and the capitulum is slightly more lax.</paragraph>
